05581nam a22010575i 9780520926141DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20191999cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2020758608  a97805209261417 a10.1525/97805209261412doi  a(DE-B1597)520648  a(OCoLC)1058901201  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aGE185.S54 4aGE185 .S54 D83 2000 7aNAT0000002bisacsh04a333.70979441 aDuane, Timothy P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aShaping the Sierra :bNature, Culture, and Conflict in the Changing West /cTimothy P. Duane. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2019] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (623 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures, Maps, and Tables -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- t1. The Range of Light -- t2. Theoretical Foundations -- t3. The Exodus to Exurbia -- t4. Economics and the Environment -- t5. Ecotransformation and Amenity Values -- t6. The Fragmented Landscape -- t7. Politics and Property -- t8. Managing Exurban Growth -- t9. Planning and Politics -- t10. Habitats and Humanity -- t11. Reinhabiting the West -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe rural west is at a crossroads, and the Sierra Nevada is at the center of this social and economic change. The Sierra Nevada landscape has always been valued for its bounty of natural resource commodities, but new residents and an ever-growing flood of tourists to the area have transformed the relationship between the region's nature and its culture. In an engaging narrative that melds the personal with the professional, Timothy P. Duane—who grew up in the area—documents the impact of rapid population growth on the culture, economy, and ecology of the Sierra Nevada since the late 1960s. He also recommends innovative policies for mitigating the negative effects of future population growth in this spectacular but threatened region, as well as throughout the rural west.Today, the primary social and economic values of the Sierra Nevada landscape are in the amenities and ecological services provided by its wildlands and functioning ecosystems. Duane shows how further unfettered population growth threatens the very values which have made the Sierra Nevada a desirable place to live and work. A new approach to land use planning, resource management, and local economic development—one that recognizes the emerging values of the landscape—is necessary in order to achieve sustainable development, Duane claims. Weaving personal experience with outstanding scholarship, he shows how such an approach must explicitly recognize the importance of values and the application of an environmental land ethic to future development in the area.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEnvironmental policyzSierra Nevada (Calif. and Nev.) 0aEnvironmental policyzSierra Nevada (Calif. and Nev.). 0aEnvironmental policyzWest (U.S.) 0aEnvironmental policyzWest (U.S.). 0aSustainable developmentzSierra Nevada (Calif. and Nev.) 0aSustainable developmentzSierra Nevada (Calif. and Nev.). 7aNATURE / General.2bisacsh  a1960s.  aacademic.  acultural studies.  aculture.  aecology.  aeconomic.  aeconomy.  aethics.  afinance.  agreen living.  aland planning.  aland use.  alandscape.  amoney.  anatural resources.  anatural world.  anature.  apolicy change.  apopulation growth.  apopulation.  aregional.  aresource management.  arural.  ascholarly.  asierra nevada.  asocial studies.  asustainability.  asustainable living.  asustainable.  atourism.  atourist.  atrue story.  awestern sta